data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, so there's nothing to migrate on that front. It uses `Thread.Start`/`Join`, which still work in .NET 8.

However, the idiomatic .NET 8 approach replaces raw threads with `Task`/`Parallel`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` migration notes** (for when you do encounter it):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — removed entirely |
| Cancelling work | Use `CancellationToken` with cooperative cancellation |
| Timeout-based abort | Use `Task.WhenAny` + `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |

**Pattern to replace `Thread.Abort`:**
```csharp
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

await Task.Run(() =>
{
    foreach (var step in steps)
    {
        cts.Token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // do work
    }
}, cts.Token);
```

Your current code is safe to migrate as-is, but switching to `Parallel.ForEach` gives you better thread-pool utilization.
